chatted with Mrs Mac Donald, & tried to be patient with the continuous racket of fire crackers, fire works, etc.

Chicago, 4. Juli 1888
10 Uhr Abends
Liebe Kinder
die inliegenden Zeugnisse, die mir heute Abend durch die Post zugekommen? sind, haben mir große Freude gemacht, denn sie beweisen, daß Ihr Eure Schulzeit gut angewendet habt. – Überrascht haben mich einige der Censuren. Zum Beispiel, daß du, Anna in Deutsch Lesen, statt a nur ab hast: – Wer liest denn besser, als Du? Und in Geographie c? Das ist wohl die Folge davon, daß wir den Globus

weggegeben haben. Wenn ich mich recht erinnere warst Du in der Millard’schen Schule in der Geographie sehr gut. – Daß Walther in Französisch a (ausgezeichnet) haben soll und Anna nur ab will mir auch nicht recht einleuchten. – Im Rechnen scheint Ihr beide nur so-so zu sein (b), was mich aber bei der Verrücktheit der Aufgaben nicht besonders wundert. Wahrscheinlich hätte ich selbst, wenn mir immer solche elende Schacher-Exempel aufgegeben worden wären, auch keine bessere Censur bekommen.

Ich wiederhole aber, daß ich mit den Zeugnissen im Allgemeinen sehr zufrieden bin und sende Euch jedem einen herzhaften Kuß dafür, den die Mutter für mich auszahlen mag.
Der heutige Tag war hier nur sehr mäßig warm, theilweise sogar kühl und seit halb 9 Uhr Abends regnet es nicht gerade stark, aber dauerhaft. Ich kam, da die Setzer heute rascher fertig werden wollten, schon um halb 4 Uhr von der Office?, schlief, badete, las, aß ein ausgezeichnetes gebratenes Huhn (halb), spielte dann auf der Bank vor der Thür mit

Bruder Paul 66 und plauderte mit Frau McDonald bis gegen 9 Uhr, während in der Straße ein förmlicher Höllenlärm von fire crackers und Brunclear tobte. Ich erinnere mich keines 4. Juli in Chicago, wo in unserer Gegend so schauderhaft viel geschossen und gefeuerwerkt worden wäre wie diesmal. Aber da ich mich mit viel Geduld gewappnet hatte, hab ich es ohne sonderliche Beschwerde ertragen. – Ich will nur hoffen, daß bei Eurer Feuerwerkerei kein Unglück geschehen ist. Nehmt Euch nur auch mit dem Rudern und Schwimmen in Acht.
Nun herzlichste Grüße und Küsse an Mutter und Eddy. Sobald ich höre, daß die Feuerwerk-Sendung gut angekommen ist und kein Unheil gestiftet hat, werde ich Nützlicheres schicken. Gute Nacht HR.

Chicago, February 19th 1872
My dear daughter
Having a few moments to spare of my 
Collectors Office, I cannot them 
to any better purpose than to write you
a few lines.  For, with all the exhausting
work I have to do, it is impossible fo
me to write my private letters at any
other? regular time.  If Whenever I do
have time I write you very long
letters and at other times only a few lines.  
If, at some future time, you should
have to edit a newspapering collect
some five or six millions of dollars for the
government at the same time, I would
never think of blaming you for any 
irregularity in your private correspondence.

Yesterday, I mailed a letter to 
grandmother, containing a little story which
ma and Gert have written for our
Sunday paper along with a five dollar
greenback which they got paid for it.  There
will be no difficulty, I expect, in exchanging
the bill for at least 6 1/4 thalers?.  Ma
and Gerty enjoyed the idea of composing 
story, hugely, and were on the tiptoe
of expectation after I had taken their
manuscript to my office to hand it to 
the compositors.  They, of course, do not
believe, that the little story has any
literary merits, nor do they propose to
continue the business, but the thing
has been a very agreeable pastime and
has had an excellent effect in preventing 
ma from brooding over her condition
and from getting the blues.  
That her health has improved of
late, there is no doubt, although her nervous
very unclear of late, and is now nearly as tall, as you.

attacks have not entirely disappeared.  On two
Saturdays she has been able to enjoy a
carriage drive and last Saturday, Febry 10th
she could even be present (for a few 
hours) at an exceedingly pleasant evening
entertainment in the 12th Street Turnerhall
which is less than a mile from our house.
She, of course, had to drive there in
a carriage.  After I had taken her home
and put her to bed, I returned to the
Hall, where Gerty had been remaining 
with Wetzlers'? and Wash. Hering's? and
took part in the dancing which 
commenced at midnight.  We had a
very pleasant time, indeed, and I was 
glad that Gerty, for once, had a change
from the dull routine of housekeeping.  to
morrow I shall take her to hear Watchel
sing in the Postillion of Lonjumeau.  The German
opera is here for only three nights.  They 
are playing at the same "Globe Theater" in
Lisbeth came to see us last Saturday, she has grown very

Desplaines street between Washington and Madison
whence, several winters ago, you and I 
walked home to Chicago Avenue in 35 minutes.
The house being so small (it was rebuilt
18 months ago but is yet scarcely as large as the
Dearborn? street theater was), they charge an enor
mous admission price. - four dollars and have
sent us only four tickets for each performance.
That does not go very far, since Hesings? and
Pietich and Rapp? all want to go.  So I
shall go there only once with Gertrud.
For a few days we have had 
fine spring weather, but to day a terribly
cold wind blows from the West, across the
parries, almost strong enough to knock one
down on the street.  We have to wait for steady
strong mild weather before we can think
of removing to some other house and taking care 
of our little boy as well, as he is not taken care of
Please remember me with all our friends
Yours truly Hermann Raster

Chicago, February 24th 1872
My dear daughter
A few days ago your letter of February 3rd was received 
I am very happy to learn that you continue to enjoy 
good health and seem to be pleased with your staying in Europe.  
I might add that I am almost sorry for your not taking
part in balls, if I did not place implicit confidence
in the good judgment of grandma, who is better able to
say what becomes a young girl in Germany than I am.  But I 
wish that you should enjoy the theater as often as convenient,
because after you return here, you will have very little
chance to see good German performances, - unless by that
time young Olterstedt?, who now acts as prompter for Mrs
Thielmann? for 10 dollars a week, should have developed
into a first class actor.  
By a letter, written a few days ago by mama you
will have been informed of the improvement of her health. She
is now able to take short walks regularly, whenever the weather
and the condition of the streets permits her to.  On Saturday afternoons

I usually hire a fine carriage for two or three hours and we
drive around town; - some day on the far Southside, sometimes
North or West.  To day we drove from our cottage through Center
Avenue to Van Buren street, then through Sangamon to Washington 
street and, by way of Union Park to Mr? Hesings present residence,
684 West Washington street, between Robey? and Lincoln.  We stopped there
for half an hour with Mrs Hesing and admired the fine paintings
and stairway which they have brought from Italy.  For instance, they
have a beautiful, life like bust of Mr. Hesing, sculpted from
the finest white marble, almost as pure as alabaster, which
has cost 1750 francs at? Rome.  Again they have large, life-size
portraits of young M. Hesing, his wife, and Mrs. Hesing, 
painted at Rome by our celebrated Chicago artist Healy.  They
have cost heaps of money, I believe 600 or 800 francs each,
but I declare that I shall not waste money in this way,
as long as the very best and most elaborately and artistically
untouched? life size photograph - portraits can be had at
Albert's in Minchen for 100 guilden.  It is not im
possible that I may have a chance next year to have our
pictures taken here; for, among the many plans and
schemes which from the subject of our conversations, is the

proposition to go to Germany in the spring of 1872 and 
attend the great Industrial Exhibition at Vienna.  By that
time your education could be finished, as far as it can be
done by teachers, - we could travel together through Germany,
leaving the little boy with grandma in the meantime, and
return to Chicago in the fall.  
However, at the present moment such plans may appear
a little visionary yet, for there is a cast amount of work
to do until then.  This being the year of a presidential election,
I have to devote much more of my time to politics than at any
time since 1868.  Then there is the question of a new house.  At
first I had expected to sell our lot in Dearborn street and purchase
a house with 50 feet of ground in some eligible neighborhood
on the West side.  But of late I have become satisfied that this
won't do, since the prices, asked for such houses, are
really outrageous.  In some cases people ask quite double what
the houses would have been worth before the fire.  Such being the
case, I am now nearly resolved upon building a new house
on our old place in Dearborn street, if I can get such a one built,
as I want, for about 7000 dollars.  The house i to be of brick
with stone front and we have been contriving plans for it all
this week.  We mean to build up the whole width of 25 feet,

leaving an alley between our house and Voight's (who have, already, re
built a two story frame house, which, when finished and painted
will, I trust, present a better appearance than their old one.  The 
main building is to be 30 feet deep and the extension about the same,
but 8 feet less in width, thus giving all the rooms? the best of light
and ventilation.  Perhaps you will understand our plan best from a diagram; thus:

The kitchen and laundry would be in the 
basement under the extension, 16 feet wide
and 28 feet long, while that part of
the basement under the main building would
be used only as a cellar, furnace room etc.
Of the backyard, about 60 feet would be
partitioned off by a trellis to be covered with vines, behind which
a little indispensable house would be screened. 
Such is our plan, but as yet it is only a plan, nothing more.  Be
fore executing it, I have to consider many things: the cost of the
building material and labor especially, which at present time, is
extravagantly higher and will remain so for several months yet.  At the
very best the house could not be finished before October or November.  
Meanwhile we have to look about for some other house to remove
to by the first of May.  It will not be quite easy to find one
suited to our purpose, since most of the houses which are to rent
on the West side, are of the same kind as our brick house in Chicago Avene
was, and mama declines to live in a house where there is so much
climbing of stairs.  Yet, with a little patience, I expect to find what we want.
Now, my dear Mathilde, you have got a letter three times as long as any
you ever wrote me and I hope you will reciprocate.  For, surely?, you cannot
have less leisure to write letters, than I have.  I desire you to give my best respects 
to grandmama and Mr. Riett?.  Your affectionate father Hermann Raster

Chicago; 391 West Jackson street
May 12th 1872
My dear daughter
At last we are well settled in our
new home and have had a very agreeable
house warming too in the shade of a surprise
party on my birthday.  About that, however, I 
need not write you, since I have sent you
a copy of the Staetszeitung? containing a report
upon the subject, and since Gertrud in her last 
letter has given you all further details.  I may 
add that both, mama and Gertrud, did the
honor of the occasion very gracefully, Gertrud
moving about among the visitors like a princess,
having a pleasant word and smile for every
one and engaging in conversation in either
English or German without the slightest hesitation.
Her pronunciation of the English which was
horrible beyond all conception when she first
came here, has improved in a remarkable
manner, though it bears yet a strong foreign
accent. - We were all very, very happy on
that evening which almost wiped out the

memory of that dreadful Monday thirty weeks ago.
Thirty weeks - only!  Now, they've passed, they
seem to have been a mere dram, commencing
with a terrible nightmare but ending with quite
a pleasant awakening.  The remembrance of those
many keepsakes, mementoes of the past, which
no money can replace, for a time weighted heavily
upon my mind, but in the restless whirlpool of
active life the sad impressions left by that 
horrible October day have gradually vanished and
the duties and cares of the present crowd out the
sorrow of the past.  
Of our new house I have, in a 
former letter, given you a pretty complete
description.  Fitting it up has occupied most
of our spare time for the last six weeks.
Apart from the contents of the wardrobes
and linen. shelves (drawers.)  you would find everything 
about the house much nicer and more elegant
than we have ever had it in any of our former
houses. _ We have gone and fresh Brussels
carpets in all, except the two small extension
rooms; a highly ornamental mirror reaching 
from the floor to the ceiling of the parlor;
a beautiful parlor set of finely carved black 
walnut, inlaid with French walnut and ebony, and

covered with splendid crimson silk brocatelle;
lambrequins to match the furniture over all
the front windows (crimson silk in parlor,
green up? in the three window'ed large front bed.
room); a bedroom set (bedstand? and bureau
only) as fine as any of those which the fashion.
able furniture dealers on the Southside used to
charge 200 or 250 dollars for; - a rosewood
seven - octane piano of Julius Bauer's make, the
selling price of which is 600 dollars while I 
got it at  trifle below the cord-price, viz: 300
dollars.  You know, that we editors are a 
privileged clan here and get most things far
cheaper than other people, if we want to.  On this
occasion I have not been slow to use all
my opportunities. Our stock of china and kitchen
utensils is also more complete than it was in
the old house and the service of silver I got
on my birthday is a very acceptable addition 
to our dining room furniture.  The mantelpiece
in the front parlor is ornamented by that beau
tiful group of Rogers': "One more shot!" and
I have ordered its counter piece "The wounded 
scout" from New York. _ Pictures I expect to get
from Berlin.  A new sewing machine has done excellent
service already and will do more yet.  It having treadles

for both feet, mama works at it with the
greatest ease.
Our little boy is with us since two weeks
yesterday.  It took him several days to become
familiar with our faces and to change his be
wildered state into smiles. Yet he has a bad habit 
of being awake and crying of nights while generally
he keeps pretty quiet during the daytime.  We had a 
girl, quite green, to take care of the baby, but she
was so terribly stupid and awkward that we were
almost glad, she left last Friday.  For, instead of
being a help, she was actually a hindrance to everybody.  
I have advertised for another girl but none have 
applied yet.  Poor mama suffers quite perceptibly
under the great tribulations the the merely little boy
causes her.  It is too much for her strength and I
tremble lest the continued exertions and cares should
endanger her health, scarcely restored.  What she most
needs is exercise in fresh air, but as long as we
do not get a good reliable girl to take care
of the baby, she can have very little of it.  Altogether
I  knew very well what I was about when I preferred
the baby's staying with Miss Sherman.  The mere
satisfaction of having him with us would be very poor
consideration for the shattering of his mother's health.  _ Girls
are exceedingly rare here.  Ten are advertised for before 
one offers.  
Although we have had very chilly days yet, spring
has appeared here with a suddenness utterly incredible.
Ten days ago all trees were bleak and bare as in mid
winter; _ to day they are all covered with the most luxurious foliage
and the lilac is full blown.  Nothing equals the beauty of the
residence streets in our part of the city, unclear as they are by continuous
rows of trees on each side.  Little Jefferson Park is a perfect gem.
Your affectionate father, H Raster

Chicago, 3. November 1872
My dear daughter
At last the election has come so near that I may
look forward to a time of comparative rest, though
all troubles will not be over yet by any means when
Grant should be reelected.  Just at present the city is suffering
under a most unexpected calamity.  All of a sudden almost
all the horses - at least eight out of every ten fo them - 
have become disabled by a disease which, having
originated in Canada, has within two weeks spread
over all our Northern states.  The disease is a kind of
influenza (Rotz) and seems to be spread by a peculiar 
condition of the atmosphere, since thousands of horses
catch it who have not been near any other horse.
Only in very few cases the animals die, but in all cases
they are utterly disabled for several days or weeks.  The 
calamity came over us as suddenly as a fire.  Friday fore
noon (day before yesterday) the streets were yet crowded, as usual, 
with all sorts of vehicles and teams, but towards evening they
were all but deserted by the quadrupeds. Since yesterday no

streetcars are running upon any line, no express wagons,
no hacks are to be seen; - only, at rare intervals, a
buggy or a private carriage, driving slowly and cautiously, 
but the house should be heated and catch the disease im
medietely.  - In a livery stable near our house 175 out of
200 horses are sick; - of the 60 horses of J.V. Farwell & Co.
every one.  The express companies cannot deliver their packages, 
freight cannot be transferred between the different railroads,
grocers and tradespeople cannot deliver goods to customers, the
milkman stops their rounds, the work on buildings has to
be discontinued because the materials cannot be hauled on;
tens of thousands of people, living from 2 to 4 miles from
their offices or stores have to walk the whole distance; doctors
cannot visit their patients: - in fact it is almost impossible
to enumerate the hardships caused by this singular visitation.  
The lesson account of the stoppage of business is enormous
and if the present condition should continue for only two
weeks the damage will not be less than what could have been
caused by a conflagration destroying a hundred houses or more.  - However,
we must bear it, that's all.
Your last letter of October 15th has pleased me greatly because it
was so much better in composition and in handwriting than many preceding ones.

Butwhat displeases me greatly is: that you have never yet to
my recollection except once answered to my often repeated demand to practice
English - writing.  It seems that all, I have written you upon 
that subject goes for nothing.  Now, remember, I have not snet
you to Germany in order to un-Americanize you, but to 
give you a good German education beside an American one.  If,
after you stay in Germany, I should find that your English
education has become defective, you will have to go to school
here again, the same as Lizzie Skinner, who you remember, was
a schoolgirl yet in her twentieth year.  It is almost impossible that,
with an utter absence of practice, your knowledge of English should
not have been learned.  But, even if that should not be the 
case, you cannot, certainly, have improved it.  At your present
age you should have a tolerably fair knowledge of English literature,
of which, I am afraid, you actually know next to nothing.  And
yet the Local Library offers you a more complete collection
of good English books than you would have had at your service here.  
Dancing and going to balls is all very well in its place, but 
it is not well, if it makes you lose eight of the principal
object of your stay in Europe.  
In our family everything goes well, at least with Mama,
Gertrud and little Eddy.  My own health might be better.  For several weeks,

I have been suffering from a mechanical difficulty in breathing which,
to say the least, is very annoying, though by no means dangerous.
It is the result of too close application to my editorial work
and will, undoubtedly, pen? away as soon as my labor is some
what lightened, which it will be after election. - All others are getting
on well and merrily.  Little Eddy cannot yet walk or talk, but
he has considerable of a will of his own and proves it by
tremendous crying whenever he fails to get immediately what
he wants.  His general health is good and his face like a red
apple, but his limbs are yet rather feeble.  Well, if, at 
least, he can walk next spring, that will do.
Since last Tuesday we have a new girl, who is tidy,
a good cook, very neat and intelligent, but _ (there is always a 
but with servant girls in this country)  - we are just now exceedingly vexed
at her; she having gone to her parents this afternoon at 1 o'clock promis
ing to be back at 7, since we wanted to go to an evening entertainment - 
and not having returned yet at a quarter past 9.  - Of course, we could not leave 
the little girl Irma? alone with the baby and have, therefore, had to 
forego our entertainment.  - As yet we are not yet resolved upon
what to do, - whether to dismiss her on the spot or not.  
Yesterday I received the chromot? which I had ordered at Berlin.
They are beautiful and certainly of the best, ever published in Germany.  _ They are:
1. Mondaufgang am Beine See; 2. auf dem Schocherthal; 3. Hafen in Winter v. Meyerheim? 4. Rinnenhefer?
5. Waldeinsamkeit im unclear, 6. Stubbenfall?, besides a couple of smaller  "Genrebilden"? - I shall
have them framed this week.  The spare? over the mantelpiece has been reserved by
Ma for the picture of your first? mother.  
Remember all of us to Grandma, Mr Rein, & Miss Frankel ise?
yours truly
Hermann Raster

Nurnburg unclear Adler, 29. Juni 1877 (3)
Friday morning, in spite of drizzling fog and rain
we climbed up to the Veste Coberg, a beautiful structure,
much finer and grander than the Wartburg. _ In the 
afternoon we drove out to Neuses, the place of residence of
the poet Ruckert and thence to castle Kallenburg, a beautiful
residence of the duchess of Coburg.  Thus, after all, we were well repaid
for our stay at that place. _ Saturday morning we went to Lichtenfels
and visited the grandstand most picturesque of all modern
church buildings in Germany, the Vierzehn Heiligen, where we mingled among
thousands of pilgrims and were half intoxicated with the devilish pious
nonsense.  This unclear in every respect the most interesting incident of

My dear daughter
Your letter of January 4th I received this morning
at my office where I had had to wade 
my way through heavy drifts of snow and whence
I returned this evening wet up to the knees and
steaming? from perspiration?.  For this, really, is the
most trying winter season I have yet gone through
out West here. And, unclear, we are comparatively
lucky in a large city where even the heaviest
snowfall cannot, for longer than a day, withstand
the head of hundreds of thousands of feet.  Terrible,
beyond all power of imagination, have been the 
sufferings of the poor settlers upon the bleak
parries of Minnesota, Iowa, Nebraska and Kansas.
Entire families have been destroyed there by
the intensely cold weather; hundreds of 
people, having been caught in the snowstorms

upon the open plains have been frozen along
with their teams, _ in some cases almost
within calling distance of the nearest settlement.  
If Compared with such calamities our own
little inconveniences and discomforts dwindle down
to nothing.  What, if we can't go out to
"Genevieve of Brabant" this evening or
attend the closing out sale of Farwells retail
dry goods department.  Some other day will do as well.
In the meantime, while the fierce snow storm
which has not yet exhausted its force is raging
in the street and rattling at our windows, we
are snugly ensconced in our comfortably heated,
gas-lit parlor, gossiping a little about the
strange news, grandma has written us in regards 
to aunt Ellen, cutting capers with little Eddy
who is in constant danger of being eaten raw 
by his parents, then again listening to the 
merry strains of Offenbachs music high Gertrud
is playing for us - little Eddy all the while
railing himself on tiptoe and touching the

Keys of the piano with his tiny little fingers
Thus we spend our evening in perfect com
fort with no particular care wishing
upon our minds except the arrangements
of the details of our trip to Europe
But whether you would enjoy such quiet
contentment as well as we do, commences to
be quite a serious question with us.  You have,
it seems, become so accustomed to your
associations in Germany and so fond of a
class of social pleasures which, here, we
can scarcely offer you, that grave doubts
arise sometimes whether you have not
withdrawn the roots of your life entirely
from the soil of your native country
However, we shall see about that when
we meet out there.  I cannot expect you
to see Germany with my eyes, nor can
I see her with yours, but there is a bare
possibility that somehow or other our views
of the subject may become reconciled with each other

The severe winter weather has been a
serious setback for the rebuilding of our city.  Happily
almost al great buildings, unclear last season, were
under roof when the cold weather set in, but the
finishing of the insides has been greatly retarded.  Our
own building is approaching completion, but the new
press (costing 21,000 dollars, capable of printing 10,000
sheets on both sides in an hour) has not yet arrived
here from Philadelphia and may be delayed for several
weeks more.  The best we can hope is to move
into the building by March 1st.  Hence, I shall
scarcely have time to begin to feel comfortable
in the new quarters, before I shall be obliged to
leave for Europe.  
Of the splendor and grandeur of most
of the new buildings on the Southside you could not
by stretching your imagination to the utmost, form an 
idea.  I hope that by spring there will be no lack 
of good stereoscopic views of all the finest buildings
of the city and I shall then stuff my trunk with them.  
Maybe they will make you feel homesick
I send my best love to Grandma and friend? Rien
Your affectionate father
H Raster
